a Peak and Naganimora. Among the most unspoiled areas in the area is a waterfall that can be seen close to the Veda summit. Veda mountain is about 70 kilometres away from Mon. Chui, Longwa, and Shangynu are three of the few settlements in the area that are worthwhile stopping by. Mon is home to many fascinating things, such as the possibility of having part of your body in India and another part in Myanmar, provided you choose to be in Longwa, the largest hamlet in the Mon district and a bordering village with Myanmar. A significant landmark in Longwa is the chief's residence, where he lives with his 60 spouses. 4. Mokokchung Mokokchung, which is home to the Ao tribe, is frequently referred to as Nagaland's brightest and most attractive area. Mokokchung, which is steadily growing in popularity as a tourist destination in Nagaland, is renowned for its rich customs, festive spirit, and warmth. Longkhum, one of its locations, is well acclaimed for being a heaven for those who love the outdoors. Since farming is the area's primary industry, festivals held around the planting and harvesting seasons are likely to improve the visitor's experience. Visitors may fall in love with Mokokchung's gorgeous surroundings, which are covered in Rhododendron across the hills. This location is well-known for its cultural handicrafts and handloom as well as for the animist cult known as Limapur. The District Museum, the Town Main Park, the Unman village (which is recognised as the oldest and largest), and the Ao village are some of the well-known tourist attractions in the area. Ungma, the first settlement established by the Ao when they arrived in Nagaland from Chungliyimti, is another popular destination in the Mokokchung district. Ungma is frequently referred to as the Ao tribe's living museum. Chuchuyimlang, commonly known as the festival village, is a tourist destination that one can also explore. The Ao Nagas festivities are enthusiastically observed in this village. Besides these locations, tourists can also visit Changtongya, Mokokchung Park, and the Mokokchung District Museum. 5. Wokha The hills and lush terrain, which are characteristic of the state, get livelier and more beautiful when you enter Wokha. Numerous plants overflowing with colourful blooms, fresh and luscious fruits, and freely flowing rivers will allure guests with their loveliness. Additionally, you may purchase deliciously fresh fruit. The tribe known as the Lotha lives in this area. An important destination in the Wokha region is a touristic village near Riphyim, which is well-known for its breathtaking views of a dam on the Donyan River. With a summit elevation of 1969 metres, Mountain Tiyi in the Wokha region is another well-liked tourist destination for the mesmerising scenery of Nagaland. Also, don't pass up the opportunity to observe the River Doyang from the mountaintop in a way that has never been seen before. The Nagas consider Mount Tiyi to be a sacred site because they think it is where the spirits of the dead reside. We may soothe our adventurous character by hiking to the impressive Mount Tiyi, which provides us with lush surroundings the entire way. As we hike up the mountain, we will learn more about the legends that are connected to it with the help of their famous folklore sung by them. Do not worry about getting there because the closest airport and train station are in Dimapur, from which we can take a taxi or a bus to Wokha. 6. Khonoma Green Village Khonoma Green Village, one of Nagaland's most undisturbed landscapes, is the product of consistent ethical living. This valley is a beautiful vacation location and a well-liked tourist attraction in Nagaland because of the tranquil scenery, clean air, and tranquil setting. Each home we will see here has been completely handmade using only crude ingredients that have been recycled or come from the earth. It is a place where the Angami community lives off of farming, spinning, and handlooms to provide for the