 of Nagaland, one of its sibling states of seven sisters. Nagaland is a mysterious, far-flung region that offers a genuinely unique travel encounter in India. Perhaps the most colourful of all the Indian states, this one is home to over 15 tribes and a remarkable 36 local dialects. Some of its well-known tribes include the Changs, Kacharis, Lothas, and others. It is undeniable that Nagaland is a state with a diverse range of cultures, which is why it is known as the "Land of the Festivals." Each tribe has a separate space in this state to practice its own rites and traditions. And this is the reason why there are so many festivals planned throughout the entire year. In fact, the state government of Nagaland recently created the now-famous Hornbill Event, a kind of umbrella festival that aims to unite all the various cultures and tribes in Nagaland under a single category of the population. After learning so much about Nagaland, we can be certain that visiting this state, if it's on a traveller's bucket list, would be a colourful experience. Let's discover some of Nagaland's tourist attractions. 1. Dimapur The state of Nagaland welcomes you with an open heart and warm hospitality at Dimapur, which serves as its entry point. It is a town with beautiful scenery, well-maintained roads, and a well-planned layout. The town offers a wide range of options to history scholars and nature admirers. The 13th-century Kachari Ruins, which are said to be proof of the Ahom intrusion of the area, are one of Dimapur's most beautiful locations. Dimapur will undoubtedly appeal to nature enthusiasts since it will lead them on a memorable journey. Seithekima village and Kuki Dolong village are some of the top locations in Dimapur that are well-known for tourist attractions since they are ideal for peace and serenity, and they are located in quiet places far away from the busy and hectic city life. 2. Kohima The highland capital of Nagaland, one of India's seven sister states, is Kohima. 