 farming. The district features challenging terrain with high slopes, excluding the foothills. Although Mon doesn't have many tourist attractions, it nonetheless draws lots of visitors from all over the world. The well-known tourist destinations in this region are Veda Peak and Naganimora. Among the most unspoiled areas in the area is a waterfall that can be seen close to the Veda summit. Veda mountain is about 70 kilometres away from Mon. Chui, Longwa, and Shangynu are three of the few settlements in the area that are worthwhile stopping by. Mon is home to many fascinating things, such as the possibility of having part of your body in India and another part in Myanmar, provided you choose to be in Longwa, the largest hamlet in the Mon district and a bordering village with Myanmar. A significant landmark in Longwa is the chief's residence, where he lives with his 60 spouses. 4. Mokokchung Mokokchung, which is home to the Ao tribe, is frequently referred to as Nagaland's brightest and most attractive area. Mokokchung, which is steadily growing in popularity as a tourist destination in Nagaland, is renowned for its rich customs, festive spirit, and warmth. Longkhum, one of its locations, is well acclaimed for being a heaven for those who love the outdoors. Since farming is the area's primary industry, festivals held around the planting and harvesting seasons are likely to improve the visitor's experience. Visitors may fall in love with Mokokchung's gorgeous surroundings, which are covered in Rhododendron across the hills. This location is well-known for its cultural handicrafts and handloom as well as for the animist cult known as Limapur. The District Museum, the Town Main Park, the Unman village (which is recognised as the oldest and largest), and the Ao village are some of the well-known tourist attractions in the area. Ungma, the first settlement established by the Ao when they arrived in Nagaland from Chungliyimti, is another popular destination in the Mokokchung