s entry point. It is a town with beautiful scenery, well-maintained roads, and a well-planned layout. The town offers a wide range of options to history scholars and nature admirers. The 13th-century Kachari Ruins, which are said to be proof of the Ahom intrusion of the area, are one of Dimapur's most beautiful locations. Dimapur will undoubtedly appeal to nature enthusiasts since it will lead them on a memorable journey. Seithekima village and Kuki Dolong village are some of the top locations in Dimapur that are well-known for tourist attractions since they are ideal for peace and serenity, and they are located in quiet places far away from the busy and hectic city life. 2. Kohima The highland capital of Nagaland, one of India's seven sister states, is Kohima. The anglicised name "Kohima" was given by the British; the original name, "Kewhira," was drawn from the Kewhi flowers that are seen in the area. The capital city of Nagaland, Kohima, is among the most endearing locations to explore. Although Kohima was introduced to the contemporary world, it nonetheless managed to preserve its natural beauty and possess a unique, captivating grace. It is a place of tradition that has been transmitted down through the ages and is renowned for its dreamy setting and unspoiled charm. It is 1500 metres above sea level and is surrounded by charming hills, lush trees, and a gorgeous setting that makes it the perfect location for trekking, camping, and hiking, making it the go-to spot for all adventure aficionados. The Naga and Kulkis tribes live in Kohima, which the British developed, and can astound one with their autonomy and the magical and vibrant culture that they follow. As the scene of a bloody war with the Japanese that lasted 64 days during World War II, Kohima will go down in history as a significant event. The Commonwealth War Cemetery, which is among the most visited places in the area, is home to thousands of World War II veterans. The cemetery houses almost 1400 burials. This location offers a window into the way of life of the native Angami tribe, which dominates this area. The city has far more to offer visitors than that, including a museum, zoo, sanctuary, valleys, autonomous communities, and so on. On the other part of Kohima, known as Tseminyu, there are numerous historic graveyards, ruins, and settlements that have been deserted to engage aficionados. Also, one can't simply afford to miss places like Japfu Peak and the Naga Heritage Village. 3. Mon Mon, one of Nagaland's top tourist destinations, is renowned for its pleasant setting. Perhaps the fascinating feature of this town is its inhabitants and their colourful and distinctive culture and clothing. There are many charming villages close by that may give you a better understanding of Naga life. Mon, the abode of the Konyaks Nagas, offers visitors singular and utterly enthralling view of tattooed faces donning feathered loincloths. Because they claim they are Noah's progeny, the Konyaks practise farming. The district features challenging terrain with high slopes, excluding the foothills. Although Mon doesn't have many tourist attractions, it nonetheless draws lots of visitors from all over the world. The well-known tourist destinations in this region are Veda Peak and Naganimora. Among the most unspoiled areas in the area is a waterfall that can be seen close to the Veda summit. Veda mountain is about 70 kilometres away from Mon. Chui, Longwa, and Shangynu are three of the few settlements in the area that are worthwhile stopping by. Mon is home to many fascinating things, such as the possibility of having part of your body in India and another part in Myanmar, provided you choose to be in Longwa, the largest hamlet in the Mon district and a bordering village with Myanmar. A significant landmark in Longwa is the chief's residence, where he lives with his 60 spouses. 4. Mokokchung Mokokchung, which is home to the Ao tribe, is frequently referred to as Nagaland's brighte