d 64 days during World War II, Kohima will go down in history as a significant event. The Commonwealth War Cemetery, which is among the most visited places in the area, is home to thousands of World War II veterans. The cemetery houses almost 1400 burials. This location offers a window into the way of life of the native Angami tribe, which dominates this area. The city has far more to offer visitors than that, including a museum, zoo, sanctuary, valleys, autonomous communities, and so on. On the other part of Kohima, known as Tseminyu, there are numerous historic graveyards, ruins, and settlements that have been deserted to engage aficionados. Also, one can't simply afford to miss places like Japfu Peak and the Naga Heritage Village. 3. Mon Mon, one of Nagaland's top tourist destinations, is renowned for its pleasant setting. Perhaps the fascinating feature of this town is its inhabitants and their colourful and distinctive culture and clothing. There are many charming villages close by that may give you a better understanding of Naga life. Mon, the abode of the Konyaks Nagas, offers visitors singular and utterly enthralling view of tattooed faces donning feathered loincloths. Because they claim they are Noah's progeny, the Konyaks practise farming. The district features challenging terrain with high slopes, excluding the foothills. Although Mon doesn't have many tourist attractions, it nonetheless draws lots of visitors from all over the world. The well-known tourist destinations in this region are Veda Peak and Naganimora. Among the most unspoiled areas in the area is a waterfall that can be seen close to the Veda summit. Veda mountain is about 70 kilometres away from Mon. Chui, Longwa, and Shangynu are three of the few settlements in the area that are worthwhile stopping by. Mon is home to many fascinating things, such as the possibility of having part of your body in India and another part in Myanmar, provided you choose to be in Longwa, the largest hamlet in the Mon district and a bordering village with Myanmar. A significant landmark in Longwa is the chief's residence, where he lives with his 60 spouses. 4. Mokokchung Mokokchung, which is home to the Ao tribe, is frequently referred to as Nagaland's brightest and most attractive area. Mokokchung, which is steadily growing in popularity as a tourist destination in Nagaland, is renowned for its rich customs, festive spirit, and warmth. Longkhum, one of its locations, is well acclaimed for being a heaven for those who love the outdoors. Since farming is the area's primary industry, festivals held around the planting and harvesting seasons are likely to improve the visitor's experience. Visitors may fall in love with Mokokchung's gorgeous surroundings, which are covered in Rhododendron across the hills. This location is well-known for its cultural handicrafts and handloom as well as for the animist cult known as Limapur. The District Museum, the Town Main Park, the Unman village (which is recognised as the oldest and largest), and the Ao village are some of the well-known tourist attractions in the area. Ungma, the first settlement established by the Ao when they arrived in Nagaland from Chungliyimti, is another popular destination in the Mokokchung district. Ungma is frequently referred to as the Ao tribe's living museum. Chuchuyimlang, commonly known as the festival village, is a tourist destination that one can also explore. The Ao Nagas festivities are enthusiastically observed in this village. Besides these locations, tourists can also visit Changtongya, Mokokchung Park, and the Mokokchung District Museum. 5. Wokha The hills and lush terrain, which are characteristic of the state, get livelier and more beautiful when you enter Wokha. Numerous plants overflowing with colourful blooms, fresh and luscious fruits, and freely flowing rivers will allure guests with their loveliness. Additionally, you may purchase deliciously fresh fruit. The tribe known as the Lotha lives in 